# No silent refactors

Refactors outside the assigned implementation scope require explicit approval or dedicated stories. Agents should avoid introducing unrelated renames, restructures, formatting-only changes, or architectural rewrites during feature implementation.

Apply this rule when:

- implementing features
- modifying existing systems
- reviewing pull requests
- validating implementation scope
- coordinating parallel development work

## Agent behavior

- If a refactor is truly required to complete the task (e.g. unblock a type or test): keep it minimal, local, and say so in the PR description; otherwise stop and ask the user or open a separate story.
- Treat wide renames, directory moves, formatter churn, and “cleanup while here” as **out of scope** unless the user explicitly approves them for this change.

## Example

```text
❌ BAD — Ticket: add filter to list → rename 20 symbols, move packages, run Black on whole tree “for consistency”

✅ GOOD — Ticket: add filter → touch list module + tests; optional tiny rename only if unavoidable, explained in PR
```
